{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534273"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:44:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:44:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.07,0.01,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50645"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"833"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18604"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with acute right ankle pain. While playing tennis 30 minutes ago, he felt a sudden \u0027popping\u0027 sensation in the back of his right ankle, followed by immediate pain and difficulty walking. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He plays tennis twice weekly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is tender to palpation of the lower third of the calf and at the base of the calcaneus. He is unable to plantarflex his right foot against resistance. Squeezing the right calf muscle produces no plantar flexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior ankle dislocation","Gastrocnemius muscle strain","Achilles tendinopathy","Calcaneal stress fracture","Complete Achilles tendon rupture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of complete Achilles tendon rupture. The history of sudden onset during sporting activity with a \u0027popping\u0027 sensation is typical. The positive Thompson test (no plantar flexion with calf squeeze) and positive Matles test (neutral hanging position of affected foot when prone) are pathognomonic signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete Achilles tendon rupture\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs 2-6 cm proximal to the calcaneal insertion, which is consistent with the palpable gap found in this patient. The combination of mechanism, examination findings, and positive special tests makes this diagnosis highly likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tendinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is typically more gradual in onset with progressive pain and stiffness. Patients maintain the ability to plantarflex the foot, and the Thompson test remains negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior ankle dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E would present with obvious deformity, severe pain, and complete inability to move the ankle joint. The mechanism would typically involve significant trauma rather than a sudden movement during sport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrocnemius muscle strain\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with pain higher in the calf, and while there may be weakness, the Thompson test would remain positive as the Achilles tendon is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcaneal stress fracture\u003C/strong\u003E presents with gradual onset heel pain that worsens with weight-bearing. There would be no sudden \u0027pop\u0027, and both the Thompson and Matles tests would be normal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thompson test (calf squeeze test) is a reliable clinical test for diagnosing Achilles tendon rupture","Complete Achilles tendon rupture typically presents with a sudden \u0027popping\u0027 sensation and immediate functional deficit","Most Achilles tendon ruptures occur during sporting activities in middle-aged recreational athletes"],"references":["Touzell A. The Achilles tendon [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/the-achilles-tendon","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:52:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:52:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7602"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":n